;; =============================================================================
;; Spec: Progress detector stage 3 — agent.invoke runtime wiring + per-category
;;       :on-anomaly policy + tool-event surfacing
;; =============================================================================
;;
;; Stage 1 (PR #784) shipped the substrate.
;; Stage 2 (PR #788) shipped the detectors, supervisor, runtime helper, and
;;   ported PR #762's review-fingerprint logic into :detector/repair-loop.
;;   But the runtime sits unconnected: agent.invoke does not yet observe
;;   live tool events, so :detector/tool-loop never fires on a real run.
;;
;; The 2026-05-05 stage-2 dogfood failed at :release before producing any
;; tool-event observations. Even after merge the wiring caveat persists —
;; Stage 2 substrate is in main but the only detector that actually fires
;; today is :detector/repair-loop, via the legacy phase-software-factory
;; call path that bypasses the runtime helper.
;;
;; Stage 3 closes the gap. After Stage 3 ships:
;;
;;   - Every agent run constructs a per-call detector runtime via
;;     pd/make-runtime + pd/make-normalizer.
;;   - The Claude CLI stream surfaces full tool-use events
;;     (:tool-name, :tool-input, :tool-output, :tool-error?,
;;     :tool-call-id) — not just tool-name flags.
;;   - The agent.invoke layer feeds each tool event through
;;     pd/observe! and consults the supervisor.
;;   - On supervisor :terminate, the in-flight LLM stream is
;;     cancelled and the controlling anomaly is recorded as the
;;     run's terminating event.
;;   - Per-category :on-anomaly overrides layer on top of the
;;     Stage 2 class-default policy, configured per-agent via
;;     prompt EDN.
;;
;; Stage 4 still owns: phase contracts + status taxonomy +
;; workflow-runner enforcement, :prompt/liveness-watchdog rename
;; + bb migrate-prompts, composite-rules for promoting heuristics
;; → mechanical, :detector/no-information-gain (depends on
;; progress ledger), structured :failure/fingerprint per tool
;; class (Stage 2 ships a stub that hashes :tool/output text),
;; :detector/text-similarity, :detector/event-motif-loop,
;; :detector/repeated-failure.

{:spec/title "Progress detector stage 3 — agent.invoke runtime wiring + per-category :on-anomaly policy"

 :spec/description
 "Wire the Stage 2 substrate into the agent.invoke LLM-stream
  boundary so detectors observe live tool events and the supervisor
  can terminate runs on mechanical anomalies. Layer per-category
  :on-anomaly overrides onto the Stage 2 class-default policy so
  individual anomaly categories can opt out of termination without
  silencing the whole class.

  Layer cake — Stage 3 contributions in **bold**:

    Layer 1 — Budget + liveness     (cost, tokens, turns, OS-wedge)
                                    [unchanged from Stage 1; rename
                                     to :prompt/liveness-watchdog
                                     deferred to Stage 4]
    Layer 2 — Event normalization   (envelope, tool profile,
                                     fingerprints) — Stage 2
                                     **+ tool-input/output/error?
                                       surfaced from the CLI stream**
    Layer 3 — Progress / anomaly    (reducer detectors, anomaly facts)
                                    [unchanged; both Stage 2 detectors
                                     fire end-to-end now]
    Layer 4 — **Supervisor policy**     class-default from Stage 2
                                        + **per-category :on-anomaly
                                          overrides + prompt-EDN
                                          configuration**
    Layer 5 — Phase contracts           [Stage 4]

  ## Why this scope

  The 2026-05-04 dogfood + #779/#781/#782/#783 series chased
  wallclock thresholds because the only supervision signal the
  agent layer had was 'how long since stdout produced a chunk?'
  Stage 2 built the detection mechanism — the within-turn loop
  detector + the across-turn repair-loop detector. Stage 3 makes
  them actually observe and act on real runs.

  Per-category :on-anomaly is the smallest policy surface that
  gives operators a way to tune behavior without touching code.
  Composite-rules and phase contracts (the rest of the policy
  surface from the Stage 1 spec) are deferred to Stage 4 because
  they require infrastructure (composite reducers, phase contract
  schema, workflow-runner enforcement) that doesn't need to ship
  alongside the basic wiring.

  ## Component layout (Stage 3 additions)

    components/llm/src/ai/miniforge/llm/
      protocols/impl/llm_client.clj
        - parse-claude-stream-line: extend tool_use case to capture
          :tool-input from the assistant's tool_use block
        - tool_result handler: emit :tool-output + :tool-error?
          + :tool-call-id chunk so tool_use and its result can
          be paired by the agent layer
        - parse-codex-stream-line: same shape for the codex backend

    components/agent/src/ai/miniforge/agent/
      detector_wiring.clj      ;; new — owns the per-invoke runtime
                               ;;   lifecycle: build runtime, build
                               ;;   normalizer, build per-agent
                               ;;   detector list from prompt EDN,
                               ;;   thread tool events through.
      core.clj                 ;; agent.invoke wraps :on-chunk to
                               ;;   intercept :tool-use chunks,
                               ;;   builds observations, feeds them
                               ;;   to the runtime, calls (pd/check
                               ;;   runtime), honors :terminate by
                               ;;   throwing :anomalies.agent/terminated.
      planner.clj
      implementer.clj
      reviewer.clj
      tester.clj
      curator.clj
      releaser.clj             ;; per-agent detector overlays read
                               ;;   from prompt EDN. The wiring is
                               ;;   shared across all six roles
                               ;;   (planner / implementer / reviewer /
                               ;;    tester / curator / releaser) —
                               ;;   no per-role copies of the
                               ;;   detector pipeline code.

    components/agent/resources/prompts/
      planner.edn
      implementer.edn
      reviewer.edn
      tester.edn
      curator.edn
      releaser.edn             ;; each prompt EDN gains a
                               ;;   :prompt/detectors block:
                               ;;     {:detectors/defaults [:tool-loop :repair-loop]
                               ;;      :on-anomaly         { … category-overrides … }}

    components/progress-detector/src/ai/miniforge/progress_detector/
      supervisor.clj           ;; handle gains a 3-arity
                               ;;   (handle policy on-anomaly anomalies)
                               ;;   that consults the per-category
                               ;;   :on-anomaly map first, then falls
                               ;;   back to the class-default policy.

  ## LLM stream extension — tool-input + tool-output

  Today's parse-claude-stream-line for assistant blocks already detects
  `tool_use` content blocks but only extracts the tool name.
  Stage 3 extends the chunk shape to also carry:

    :tool-call-id  - unique id from the CLI's tool_use block
    :tool-input    - the args map the LLM produced
    :tool-name     - already present
    :tool-use      - already present (true)

  And for `tool_result` content blocks (currently treated as plain
  text accumulation), Stage 3 emits a separate chunk:

    {:delta         \"\"
     :done?         false
     :tool-result   true
     :tool-call-id  <matches the prior :tool-use chunk>
     :tool-output   <result content from the CLI>
     :tool-error?   <bool; true when the tool reported an error>}

  The agent layer pairs each :tool-result with its earlier :tool-use
  by :tool-call-id, builds a single Observation carrying both
  :tool/input and :tool/output (event-envelope redacts both), and
  feeds it through the runtime.

  This is additive — chunks without :tool-use / :tool-result keys
  parse identically and existing :on-chunk consumers see no shape
  change.

  ## agent.invoke wiring

  agent.detector-wiring exposes:

    (with-detector-runtime [runtime ctx prompt-data] body...)
      Build a per-call runtime + normalizer from prompt-data's
      :prompt/detectors block, install a wrapper around
      (:on-chunk ctx) that intercepts tool-use/tool-result chunks
      and feeds them through the runtime, run body, and on
      supervisor :terminate, cancel the LLM stream and throw
      :anomalies.agent/terminated.

  Each role-specific agent (planner, implementer, reviewer,
  tester, curator, releaser) wraps its existing LLM call path
  in with-detector-runtime. The wrapping is one form per agent
  with no per-role logic — the wiring is data-driven from
  prompt EDN.

  Default behavior when prompt EDN omits :prompt/detectors:
  use the framework defaults [:tool-loop :repair-loop] with
  Stage 2's class-default policy and the framework's default
  config. No prompt change is required for an agent to gain
  detectors — every agent gets them automatically.

  ## Per-category :on-anomaly policy map

  Stage 2's supervisor.clj handle takes [policy anomalies] where
  policy is a class → action map. Stage 3 adds a 3-arity
  (handle policy on-anomaly anomalies) where on-anomaly is a
  category → action map consulted first:

    {:anomalies.agent/tool-loop      :terminate
     :anomalies.review/stagnation    :terminate
     :anomalies.agent/text-loop      :warn}      ;; per-category

  Resolution order:
    1. Look up the controlling anomaly's category in on-anomaly
    2. If present, that action wins
    3. Otherwise fall back to (policy class)
    4. Otherwise fall back to :continue

  Per-agent prompt EDN can override:

    :prompt/detectors
    {:detectors/defaults [:tool-loop :repair-loop]
     :on-anomaly {:anomalies.agent/tool-loop :terminate
                  :anomalies.review/stagnation :warn}}
    ;; ^^ reviewer might want to warn-not-terminate on its own
    ;;    repair-loop signal so the workflow's higher-level
    ;;    repair budget gets the final call.

  Stage 2's 2-arity (handle policy anomalies) stays for back-compat;
  it is equivalent to (handle policy {} anomalies).

  ## Termination semantics

  When the supervisor returns :terminate:
    1. agent.detector-wiring cancels the in-flight LLM stream by
       closing the underlying process (the LLM client already
       supports cancellation via the chunk-callback returning
       a :stop signal — Stage 3 wires that path).
    2. The controlling anomaly is recorded in the run's event
       log via :raw-log-ref.
    3. agent.invoke throws an ex-info whose ex-data classifies as
       :anomaly :anomalies.agent/terminated (matching the
       project-wide exception → anomaly category convention used by
       components/response — see ex-data shapes in
       response/interface) and carries the controlling anomaly map
       under a separate :controlling-anomaly key. Concretely:

         (throw (ex-info \"agent run terminated by detector\"
                         {:anomaly             :anomalies.agent/terminated
                          :controlling-anomaly <controlling-anomaly-map>
                          :run-id              <agent-run-id>}))

       The workflow runner catches this, reads :anomaly to classify
       the failure category, and reads :controlling-anomaly for the
       full evidence/category/severity payload.

  ## What Stage 3 explicitly does NOT land

  Deferred to Stage 4:
    - :prompt/progress-monitor → :prompt/liveness-watchdog rename
      and bb miniforge migrate-prompts (semantic clarification +
      sweeping migration; lands alongside the policy surface that
      gates it)
    - Phase contracts (:phase/contract block per phase)
    - Phase status taxonomy (:succeeded / :failed-contract /
      :failed-anomaly / :failed-budget / :failed-liveness /
      :failed-tool / :cancelled / :requires-human)
    - Workflow runner enforcement of contracts at phase boundaries
    - Composite-rules for promoting combined heuristics to
      mechanical anomalies
    - :detector/no-information-gain (depends on progress ledger)
    - Progress ledger reducer + :progress/advanced events
    - :detector/repeated-failure (depends on structured
      :failure/fingerprint extraction per tool class)
    - :detector/text-similarity, :detector/event-motif-loop
    - Replacing the Stage 2 stub failure-fingerprint with a
      structured parser per tool class"

